You can&#39;t do that. `switch` is a statement with the following syntax:

    switch (expr) {
      case expr:
        statements
      default:
        statements
    }

with zero or more `case` clauses and zero or one `default` clause. Your `switch` expression swallowed the cases, so there&#39;s none for `switch`, and your `case` clauses are bare in the function without a `switch`. It is also not clear at all what you would want to switch on.

The cleanest way to rewrite your example would be to use a lookup object:

    const lookup = {
      1: auto_url1,
      2: auto_url2,
      3: auto_url3,
    };
    
    let which = 1;
    func = lookup[which];
    if (func === undefined) {
      console.error(&quot;Bad which.&quot;);
    } else {
      let myTimer = setInterval(lookup[which], 10000);
      // ...
    }

For calling functions in a wanted order and repeatedly, you could take an array and store an index for the access.

For each call of the callback of `setInterval`, a function is taken out of the array and called. The index is updated and adjusted for the next access.

